 Description:
 The Avenger is a lightweight, ground-to-air missile and gun weapon system mounted on a High Mobility Multi-Purpose Wheeled Vehicle (HMMWV). The system is designed to protect against unmanned aircraft
 systems (UAS), cruise missiles, and fixed- and rotary-wing threats. The Avenger provides day/night and adverse weather operational capabilities, shoot-on-the-move functionality, rapid target engagement, and
 remote firing capability. It is highly mobile, capable of being air-dropped, helicopter-lifted, and air-transportable. The system employs up to eight Stinger missiles to counter aerial threats and is equipped with an
 M3P .50 Caliber Machine Gun for close-in ground and air defense. An Identification Friend or Foe (IFF) system is integrated to aid in identifying friendly aircraft, minimizing the risk of fratricide. The Avenger fleet
 consists of 421 systems, including 169 systems equipped with a digital Slew-to-Cue (STC) capability, which enhances target detection and engagement speed.

 The Avenger Modification - Service Life Extension Program (MOD-SLEP) addresses the obsolescence of key Avenger components to ensure the system maintains its operational capability throughout its
 Economic Useful Life (EUL).

 The Vehicle Internal Communications System (VIC) is a critical subsystem that facilitates communication between the gunner and driver. Additionally, it interfaces with the Identification Friend or Foe (IFF) system
 and missile electronics, enhancing IFF capabilities. The digital VIC-5 system replaced the analog VIC-1 system, providing improved functionality and performance.

 The Avenger Fire Control Computer (AFCC) is a critical subsystem of the Avenger Slew-to-Cue system, responsible for processing and displaying air track data to the gunner. To address this, the AFCC
 underwent software and hardware upgrades to enhance its capabilities. These upgrades enable the system to handle increased targeting capabilities provided by the latest version of the FAAD early warning
 system, ensure compliance with the latest Information Assurance (IA) requirements, and support future growth in areas such as improved fire control and longer-range engagements.

 The Mode 5 Identification Friend or Foe (IFF) system replaced the Mode 4 IFF system to comply with Department of War standards. Incorporating Mode 5 IFF into the Avenger system is critical for retaining
 cooperative target identification capabilities, ensuring the Avenger remains relevant and effective in Air Defense and Homeland Defense missions. Additionally, Mode 5 IFF quantities exceeding 421 for the
 Avenger systems will support the requirements of the Stinger Man-Portable Air Defense System (MANPADS).

 The Assured Positioning, Navigation, and Timing (A-PNT) hardware will equip the Avenger system with M-Code capability by 1QFY2027.

 The Targeting Console (TC) and AFCC are fielded exclusively to the 169 Slew-to-Cue (STC) Avenger systems. The M3P .50 Caliber Machine Gun is fielded through attrition through the supply system. The
 VIC-5, Mode 5 IFF, and A-PNT hardware are fielded to all 421 Avenger systems.

 In previous years, the Avenger MODS program also addressed upgrades to the Slew-to-Cue system, TC, and M3P .50 Caliber Machine Gun.


