Justification:
The MB7000 Base Level Common Equipment (BCE) line funds multiple systems with differing unit costs. The Unit Cost on the P40 will fluctuate year-to-year depending on the underlying mix of systems
procured.

The FY 2027 Base procurement dollars in the amount of $19.889 million supports Installation Management Command (IMCOM) requirements for new and emerging investment items, as well as the replacement
of critical equipment that is obsolete, in shortage, beyond economical repair, or over 15 years old. This BCE program is essential to modernize aging equipment subjected to continuous heavy use, particularly
where major components are no longer available due to manufacturer discontinuation. Without timely equipment replacement, the Army faces escalating maintenance costs that are no longer sustainable and
detract from other critical Base Operations Support services. In the absence of BCE procurements, garrisons are increasingly forced to lease equipment, incurring costs that are, on average, over 45% higher
than the total cost of ownership for a life cycled BCE replacement. These procurements enable the Army to meet mission requirements effectively and cost-efficiently while ensuring operational readiness across
installations.

The FY 2026 President's Budget request included $0.716 million of mandatory funding. The FY 2027 request includes $1.036 million of mandatory funding which will support the Department of the Army Criminal
Investigation Division (DACID) continuing effort to modernize the advancement of forensic equipment of the U.S. Army Criminal Investigation Laboratory (USACIL) in the disciplines of Trace Evidence, DNA
and Drug Chemistry. Procurement of emerging technologies and replacement of outdated laboratory instruments will ensure that DACID's USACIL remains a world class forensic provider supporting all Military
Criminal Investigative Organizations (MCIOs) of the Department of Defense. Further, these BCE procurement funding dollars may be used to advance criminal investigative and executive protection capabilities
across DACID for criminal investigative equipment requirements, lifecycle replacement of servers, related information technology/audio visual equipment (IT/AV), and/or technologies critical to the provision of
executive protections to high-risk personnel.

In accordance with section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110 - 181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.




