 Description:
 This funding supports the Base Emergency Communications System (BECS) program, which enhances interoperability and fielding efficiency across a broad suite of hardware and software components that
 support the Army's plan for all installations' emergency communications infrastructure. BECS enables Army commanders to effectively provide mission command communications to security, fire, medical
 services, and Emergency Management (EM). BECS will allow commanders to effectively employ first responder assets to prevent, detect, and mitigate incidents across the Strategic Support Areas at each
 Installations, Depots, and Activity (I/D/A).

 BECS capabilities refer to the standardized suite of capabilities that provide first responders Command and Control (C2) comprised of: Land Mobile Radio (LMR), Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD), Next
 Generation 9-1-1 (NG-911), Enterprise Mass Warning Notification (EMWN), and First Responder Broadband Network (FRBN). The BECS program modernizes these capabilities at 288 worldwide I/D/As.
 The BECS program was established to increase interoperability amongst the capabilities and fielding efficiency. BECS comprises a diverse array of hardware and software components requiring seamless
 interoperability to ensure efficient and effective operations within the mission and with Mutual Aid Partners, including Federal, State, Local, Tribal, and Territorial (FSLTT) dispatch centers. Emergency dispatchers
 depend on these to receive emergency Calls for Service (CFS), dispatch first responders, create incident records, and manage incidents through resolution and closure to prevent loss of life, minimize injury, and
 mitigate incidents.

 B74111 Base Support Communication provides real-time mission-critical voice and data communications for I/D/A first responders (Military Police, Fire Departments, and Emergency Medical), public safety,
 force protection, homeland security, pre-deployment logistics support, and Installation management missions via the Army LMR network in support of the Army's 2030/2040 objectives. LMR includes network
 infrastructure, dispatch and management consoles, and portable and mobile radios at 288 I/D/As (95 CONUS and 193 OCONUS), to ensure synchronized, timely, and effective emergency response. Modernized
 LMR systems will be interoperable with other BECS capabilities. LMR will transition from stand-alone to regional, to a centralized interoperable capability in the BECS-enabled public safety communication
 enterprise architecture with Internet Protocol Infrastructure as mandated by Public Law 110-283. Centralizing LMR maximizes cost-effectiveness and cybersecurity.

 LMR site requirements at each I/D/A vary based on the geography, number of end users, radio frequency towers, mutual aid partners, and the Installation dispatch concept of operations. Site-specific
 requirements are determined through government surveys and stakeholders' coordination.

 B74222 The Emergency Management Modernization Program encompasses NG-911, CAD, and EMWN capabilities in support of the Army's FY 2030/2040 objectives. Public Safety Answering Point (PSAP)
 Modernization supports the procurement of Commercial Off-The-Shelf (COTS) Non-Developmental Items (NDI) to modernize NG-911 infrastructure (Geographic Information Systems (GIS) and Location



