 Description:
 This funding line supports the Mounted Mission Command (MMC) Family of Systems (FoS) and supports the Army Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) initiative to modernize Command and Control
 (C2) systems, Infrastructure layer. The MMC FoS comprised of the the MMC-Software (MMC-S) and MMC-Transport (MMC-T) programs, as well as the Blue Force Tracking (BFT) network and replacement for
 the Mounted Family of Computer Systems (MFoCS) hardware, will replace the Joint Battle Command-Platform (JBC-P) system and complement the NGC2 solution. The MMC FoS provides the replacement
 for the legacy BFT capability, be employing hardened cyber/electronic warfare advancements that will improve data sharing and enhance C2 on-the-move (C2OTM) functionality, resulting in more reliable
 communications anytime, anywhere, in all domains.

 The MMC-T program provides next-generation transceivers, encryption devices, and satellite communication waveforms (which are hosted in the transceiver) that offer a significant improvement over the
 existing BFT-2 capability by enabling smart routing across multiple network paths (Geosynchronous Equatorial Orbit (GEO), Low-Earth Orbit (LEO), and Line of Sight (LoS)) to mitigate risks posed by denied
 environments or signal jamming. New encryption devices provide protections against electronic warfare and cyber attacks.

 The MMC-S program replaces JBC-P software on vehicles and in command posts by providing next generation C2/Situational Awareness (SA) software that offers simplicity, intuitiveness, and enhanced
 capabilities over the legacy software. MMC-S utilizes the Tactical Assault Kit (TAK), a Government-owned application, to enable convergence of Warfighting Functions and utilizes a Continuous Integration/
 Continuous Delivery (CI/CD) approach for software development.

 The MMC FoS Basis of Issue (BOI) and the proposed Army Acquisition Objective (AAO) are under development and will be validated through the Army Requirements Oversight Council (AROC). Fielding MMC
 allows the Army to divest the legacy system (JBC-P). As MMC-T hardware and MMC-S are fielded, overall cyber resilience will improve.

 Funding in FY 2027 and beyond was realigned to PE B11400 C2 Infrastructure as part of a new funding structure for the Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) investment in a modernization of Army
 Command and Control (C2) Systems. A funding line consolidation and structure change for the NGC2 investment provides clarity and transparency for the NGC2 four layered approach (Applications, Data,
 Transport, and Infrastructure).

 Justification:




